11. WHY THIS FRAMEWORK IS “BEST-IN-CLASS”
•	Clean OOPS-based POM
•	Proper BDD separation
•	Data is externalized
•	Config is governed
•	Thin root config ensures Playwright compatibility
•	Easily extendable to API, mobile, CI/CD
This is a framework you can defend in an architecture review.
________________________________________
Run Tests in a Specific Browser (Single Browser)
Your framework is ENV-driven, so the browser is selected via the BROWSER environment variable.
▶ Chromium
BROWSER=chromium npx cucumber-js
▶ Firefox
BROWSER=firefox npx cucumber-js
▶ WebKit
BROWSER=webkit npx cucumber-js
▶ Headed Mode (Debug-friendly)
BROWSER=chromium npx cucumber-js
(Headless/Headed is controlled via Playwright config or launch options.)
________________________________________
Run Tests in Parallel (Same Browser)
Cucumber supports parallel execution via --parallel.
▶ Example: 4 parallel workers in Chromium
BROWSER=chromium npx cucumber-js --parallel 4
What happens:
•	One browser instance per worker
•	Isolated contexts
•	Thread-safe execution
________________________________________
Run Tests in Parallel Across ALL Browsers (The Truth)
⚠ This is NOT natively supported by Cucumber in a single command.
Cucumber:
•	Does not understand Playwright projects
•	Cannot fan out browsers automatically
So the correct enterprise solution is multi-command orchestration.
________________________________________
Correct Way: Parallel Browsers via NPM Scripts
package.json
{
  "scripts": {
    "test:chromium": "BROWSER=chromium npx cucumber-js --parallel 4",
    "test:firefox": "BROWSER=firefox npx cucumber-js --parallel 4",
    "test:webkit": "BROWSER=webkit npx cucumber-js --parallel 4",
    "test:all": "npm-run-all --parallel test:chromium test:firefox test:webkit"
  }
}
▶ Run all browsers in parallel
npm run test:all
Each browser:
•	Runs independently
•	Uses its own workers
•	Produces its own screenshots/videos
This is how real CI pipelines do it.
________________________________________
CI-Grade Alternative (Matrix Strategy)
If you are in GitHub Actions, Azure DevOps, Jenkins, etc.:
•	Define a browser matrix
•	Run one browser per job
•	Fastest and cleanest approach
Example (conceptual):
browser: [chromium, firefox, webkit]
